{
  "filename": "slack_workflow_webhook_urls_should_not_be_disclose_metadata.json",
  "rule_id": "slack_workflow_webhook_urls",
  "title": "Slack workflow webhook URLs should not be disclosed",
  "description": "In most cases, trust boundaries are violated when a secret is exposed in a source code repository or an uncontrolled deployment environment. Unintended people who don\u2019t need to know the secret might get access to it. They might then be able to use it to gain unwanted access to associated services or resources.",
  "status": "ready",
  "defaultSeverity": "Critical",
  "category": "Security",
  "recommendation": "Review and fix according to the rule guidelines.",
  "impact": "Security risk",
  "tags": [
    "security",
    "cwe"
  ],
  "examples": {
    "noncompliant": [],
    "compliant": []
  },
  "references": [
    "https://rules.sonarsource.com/secrets/RSPEC-6717"
  ],
  "logic": {
    "node_types": [],
    "checks": [
      {
        "type": "regex",
        "pattern": "https://hooks\\.slack\\.com/workflows/T[A-Z0-9]{8,10}/A[A-Z0-9]{8,10}/\\d{10,13}/[A-Za-z0-9]{24,}",
        "message": "Slack workflow webhook URL detected in source code. Workflow webhooks are unique URLs that trigger automated workflows in Slack when called via HTTP POST requests. These URLs provide a simple way to integrate external systems with Slack workflows without requiring full API access or OAuth. Exposing workflow webhook URLs creates significant security risks: attackers can trigger workflows without authorization, potentially executing automated actions like creating channels, posting messages, updating databases, calling external APIs, or modifying workspace settings; malicious actors can spam workflow executions to consume rate limits and disrupt operations; unauthorized workflow triggers can lead to data exfiltration if workflows process or forward sensitive information; attackers can study workflow behavior by triggering them repeatedly to understand business processes; workflow webhooks may trigger costly external service calls or operations; exposed URLs enable social engineering attacks by triggering legitimate-looking notifications; and workflow rate limit exhaustion prevents legitimate automation from functioning. This is a high-severity security vulnerability requiring immediate action. Remediation steps: regenerate the compromised workflow webhook URL in Slack (Workflow Builder \u2192 Select Workflow \u2192 Settings \u2192 Regenerate URL), update all external systems and integrations with the new webhook URL, review workflow execution logs for unauthorized or suspicious triggers, audit what actions the exposed workflow performs and assess potential impact, implement webhook URL rotation policies and regular security reviews, store workflow webhook URLs in secure secret management systems (AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, Azure Key Vault), use environment variables with restricted access for runtime configuration, never commit workflow webhook URLs to version control or expose in logs, add logging and monitoring for workflow execution patterns, implement rate limiting and alerting for unusual workflow activity, restrict workflow webhook access to specific IP ranges or VPNs when possible, use different workflow webhooks for dev/staging/production environments, document all workflow webhooks and their purposes in a secure inventory, consider replacing simple webhooks with more secure Slack app integrations using OAuth, educate development teams about workflow webhook confidentiality, and ensure proper secret scanning in CI/CD pipelines to prevent future exposures.",
